<section class="section-white">
  <div class="container content-narrow">
    <h2>What Medicare Advantage Includes</h2>
    <p>Medicare Advantage plans (Part C) are offered by private insurers approved by Medicare. They cover everything Original Medicare covers, plus often add benefits Original Medicare doesn&rsquo;t include.</p>

    <h3>Common Medicare Advantage Benefits</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hospital and medical coverage</strong> &mdash; everything Part A and Part B cover</li>
      <li><strong>Prescription drug coverage</strong> &mdash; most Advantage plans include Part D built-in</li>
      <li><strong>Dental</strong> &mdash; cleanings, exams, and often more extensive work depending on the plan</li>
      <li><strong>Vision</strong> &mdash; eye exams and an allowance for glasses or contacts</li>
      <li><strong>Hearing</strong> &mdash; hearing exams and hearing aid coverage</li>
      <li><strong>Over-the-counter (OTC)</strong> &mdash; quarterly allowances for pharmacy items</li>
      <li><strong>Transportation</strong> &mdash; rides to medical appointments on some plans</li>
      <li><strong>Fitness benefits</strong> &mdash; SilverSneakers or similar gym memberships</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How Networks Work</h3>
    <p>Medicare Advantage plans use provider networks. Most are <strong>HMO</strong> (in-network only) or <strong>PPO</strong> (in-network preferred, out-of-network allowed at higher cost). Before choosing a plan, we always verify your doctors and preferred hospitals are in-network.</p>

    <h3>Copays and Maximum Out-of-Pocket (MOOP)</h3>
    <p>Instead of paying a percentage of every service like Original Medicare, Advantage plans typically use flat copays (e.g., $0 for primary care, $40 for specialist). Every Advantage plan also has an annual <strong>maximum out-of-pocket limit</strong> &mdash; once you hit it, the plan pays 100% for the rest of the year.</p>

    <h2>Is Medicare Advantage Right for You?</h2>
    <p>Medicare Advantage tends to make sense if:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You want low (or $0) monthly premiums</li>
      <li>You want extras like dental, vision, and hearing built in</li>
      <li>Your doctors are in-network</li>
      <li>You don&rsquo;t travel extensively for healthcare</li>
      <li>You&rsquo;re generally healthy and want a budget-friendly option</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Plans change every year.</strong>
      <p style="margin:8px 0 0;">Networks shift, formularies update, and benefits adjust. We do free annual reviews to make sure your Medicare Advantage plan still fits &mdash; or to switch you to one that does.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

